34 SECTION 4. ORS 656.214 is amended to read:
35 656.214. (1) As used in this section:
36 (a) “Impairment” means the loss of use or function of a body part or system due to the
37 compensable industrial injury or occupational disease determined in accordance with the standards
38 provided under ORS 656.726, expressed as a percentage of the whole person.
39 (b) “Loss” includes permanent and complete or partial loss of use.
40 (c) “Permanent partial disability” means:
41 (A) Permanent impairment resulting from the compensable industrial injury or occupational
42 disease; or
43 (B) Permanent impairment and work disability resulting from the compensable industrial injury
44 or occupational disease.
45 (d) “Regular work” means the job the worker held at injury.
[14]

HB 4119
1 (e) “Work disability” means impairment modified by age, education and adaptability to perform
2 a given job.
3 (2) When permanent partial disability results from a compensable injury or occupational disease,
4 benefits shall be awarded as follows:
5 (a) If the worker has been released to regular work by the attending physician [or nurse prac-
6 titioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] or has returned to
7 regular work [at the job held at the time of injury], the award shall be for impairment only. Impair-
8 ment shall be determined in accordance with the standards provided by the Director of the Depart-
9 ment of Consumer and Business Services pursuant to ORS 656.726 (4). Impairment benefits are
10 determined by multiplying the impairment value times 100 times the average weekly wage as defined
11 by ORS 656.005.
12 (b) If the worker has not been released to regular work by the attending physician [or nurse
13 practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] or has not re-
14 turned to regular work [at the job held at the time of injury], the award shall be for impairment and
15 work disability. Work disability shall be determined in accordance with the standards provided by
16 the director pursuant to ORS 656.726 (4). Impairment shall be determined as provided in paragraph
17 (a) of this subsection. Work disability benefits shall be determined by multiplying the impairment
18 value, as modified by the factors of age, education and adaptability to perform a given job, times
19 150 times the worker’s weekly wage for the job at injury as calculated under ORS 656.210 (2). The
20 factor for the worker’s weekly wage used for the determination of the work disability may be no
21 more than 133 percent or no less than 50 percent of the average weekly wage as defined in ORS
22 656.005.
23 (3) Impairment benefits awarded under subsection (2)(a) of this section shall be expressed as a
24 percentage of the whole person. Impairment benefits for the following body parts may not exceed:
25 (a) For the loss of one arm at or above the elbow joint, 60 percent.
26 (b) For the loss of one forearm at or above the wrist joint, or the loss of one hand, 47 percent.
27 (c) For the loss of one leg, at or above the knee joint, 47 percent.
28 (d) For the loss of one foot, 42 percent.
29 (e) For the loss of a great toe, six percent; for loss of any other toe, one percent.
30 (f) For partial or complete loss of hearing in one ear, that proportion of 19 percent which the
31 loss bears to normal monaural hearing.
32 (g) For partial or complete loss of hearing in both ears, that proportion of 60 percent which the
33 combined binaural hearing loss bears to normal combined binaural hearing. For the purpose of this
34 paragraph, combined binaural hearing loss shall be calculated by taking seven times the hearing loss
35 in the less damaged ear plus the hearing loss in the more damaged ear and dividing that amount
36 by eight. In the case of individuals with compensable hearing loss involving both ears, either the
37 method of calculation for monaural hearing loss or that for combined binaural hearing loss shall be
38 used, depending upon which allows the greater award of impairment.
39 (h) For partial or complete loss of vision of one eye, that proportion of 31 percent which the loss
40 of monocular vision bears to normal monocular vision. For the purposes of this paragraph, the term
41 “normal monocular vision” shall be considered as Snellen 20/20 for distance and Snellen 14/14 for
42 near vision with full sensory field.
43 (i) For partial loss of vision in both eyes, that proportion of 94 percent which the combined
44 binocular visual loss bears to normal combined binocular vision. In all cases of partial loss of sight,
45 the percentage of said loss shall be measured with maximum correction. For the purpose of this
[15]

HB 4119
1 paragraph, combined binocular visual loss shall be calculated by taking three times the visual loss
2 in the less damaged eye plus the visual loss in the more damaged eye and dividing that amount by
3 four. In the case of individuals with compensable visual loss involving both eyes, either the method
4 of calculation for monocular visual loss or that for combined binocular visual loss shall be used,
5 depending upon which allows the greater award of impairment.
6 (j) For the loss of a thumb, 15 percent.
7 (k) For the loss of a first finger, eight percent; of a second finger, seven percent; of a third fin-
8 ger, three percent; of a fourth finger, two percent.
9 (4) The loss of one phalange of a thumb, including the adjacent epiphyseal region of the proximal
10 phalange, is considered equal to the loss of one-half of a thumb. The loss of one phalange of a finger,
11 including the adjacent epiphyseal region of the middle phalange, is considered equal to the loss of
12 one-half of a finger. The loss of two phalanges of a finger, including the adjacent epiphyseal region
13 of the proximal phalange of a finger, is considered equal to the loss of 75 percent of a finger. The
14 loss of more than one phalange of a thumb, excluding the epiphyseal region of the proximal
15 phalange, is considered equal to the loss of an entire thumb. The loss of more than two phalanges
16 of a finger, excluding the epiphyseal region of the proximal phalange of a finger, is considered equal
17 to the loss of an entire finger. A proportionate loss of use may be allowed for an uninjured finger
18 or thumb where there has been a loss of effective opposition.
19 (5) A proportionate loss of the hand may be allowed where impairment extends to more than one
20 digit, in lieu of ratings on the individual digits.
21 (6) All permanent disability contemplates future waxing and waning of symptoms of the condi-
22 tion. The results of waxing and waning of symptoms may include, but are not limited to, loss of
23 earning capacity, periods of temporary total or temporary partial disability, or inpatient
24 hospitalization.
25 SECTION 5. ORS 656.245 is amended to read:
26 656.245. (1)(a) For every compensable injury, the insurer or the self-insured employer shall cause
27 to be provided medical services for conditions caused in material part by the injury for such period
28 as the nature of the injury or the process of the recovery requires, subject to the limitations in ORS
29 656.225, including such medical services as may be required after a determination of permanent
30 disability. In addition, for consequential and combined conditions described in ORS 656.005 (7), the
31 insurer or the self-insured employer shall cause to be provided only those medical services directed
32 to medical conditions caused in major part by the injury.
33 (b) Compensable medical services shall include medical, surgical, hospital, nursing, ambulances
34 and other related services, and drugs, medicine, crutches and prosthetic appliances, braces and
35 supports and where necessary, physical restorative services. A pharmacist or dispensing physician
36 shall dispense generic drugs to the worker in accordance with ORS 689.515. The duty to provide
37 such medical services continues for the life of the worker.
38 (c) Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, medical services after the worker’s
39 condition is medically stationary are not compensable except for the following:
40 (A) Services provided to a worker who has been determined to be permanently and totally dis-
41 abled.
42 (B) Prescription medications.
43 (C) Services necessary to administer prescription medication or monitor the administration of
44 prescription medication.
45 (D) Prosthetic devices, braces and supports.
