8 SECTION 14. ORS 659A.043 is amended to read:
9 659A.043. (1) A worker who has sustained a compensable injury shall be reinstated by the
10 worker’s employer to the worker’s former position of employment upon demand for such rein-
11 statement, if the position exists and is available and the worker is not disabled from performing the
12 duties of such position. A worker’s former position is available even if that position has been filled
13 by a replacement while the injured worker was absent. If the former position is not available, the
14 worker shall be reinstated in any other existing position that is vacant and suitable. A certificate
15 by the attending physician, as defined in ORS 656.005 (12)(b), [or a nurse practitioner authorized
16 to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] that the attending physician [or nurse
17 practitioner] approves the worker’s return to the worker’s regular employment or other suitable
18 employment shall be prima facie evidence that the worker is able to perform such duties.
19 (2) Such right of reemployment shall be subject to the provisions for seniority rights and other
20 employment restrictions contained in a valid collective bargaining agreement between the employer
21 and a representative of the employer’s employees.
22 (3) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section:
23 (a) The right to reinstatement to the worker’s former position under this section terminates
24 when whichever of the following events first occurs:
25 [(A) A medical determination by the attending physician or, after an appeal of such determination
26 to a medical arbiter or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656, has been made that the
27 worker cannot return to the former position of employment.]
28 (A) The worker cannot return to the former position of employment according to:
29 (i) The medical determination of the attending physician; or
30 (ii) Upon appeal of the attending physician’s determination, the determination of a med-
31 ical arbiter or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656.
32 (B) The worker is eligible and participates in vocational assistance under ORS 656.340.
33 (C) The worker accepts suitable employment with another employer after becoming medically
34 stationary.
35 (D) The worker refuses a bona fide offer from the employer of light duty or modified employment
36 that is suitable prior to becoming medically stationary.
37 (E) Seven days elapse from the date that the worker is notified by the insurer or self-insured
38 employer by certified mail that the worker’s attending physician [or a nurse practitioner authorized
39 to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] has released the worker for employment
40 unless the worker requests reinstatement within that time period.
41 (F) Three years elapse from the date of injury.
42 (b) The right to reinstatement under this section does not apply to:
43 (A) A worker hired on a temporary basis as a replacement for an injured worker.
44 (B) A seasonal worker employed to perform less than six months’ work in a calendar year.
45 (C) A worker whose employment at the time of injury resulted from referral from a hiring hall
